{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603220"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:35:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:35:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15730"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15730"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.02,0.62,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80848"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8421"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66170"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"7037"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"},{"type":"tags","id":"10604"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27637"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80848"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst not one of the commonest cancers in women, ovarian cancers is one of the most sinister. Its vague symptoms make early detection of the disease difficult and many patients present with the disease in an advanced state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for epithelial ovarian cancer are important to understand for prevention and screening strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a risk factor for epithelial ovarian cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiparity","Breastfeeding","Early pregnancy","Nulliparity","Combined hormonal contraception use"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiparity\u003C/strong\u003E (having multiple pregnancies) is actually protective against epithelial ovarian cancer, likely due to the reduced number of ovulatory cycles. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebreastfeeding\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined hormonal contraception use\u003C/strong\u003E are protective factors through suppression of ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENulliparity\u003C/strong\u003E is a significant risk factor for epithelial ovarian cancer. Other risk factors include late menopause, family history of ovarian or breast cancer, and increasing age. \u003Cstrong\u003EEarly pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is protective rather than a risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe protective effect of reduced lifetime ovulations supports the incessant ovulation hypothesis, which suggests that repeated damage and repair of the ovarian surface epithelium increases cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nulliparity, late menopause, and family history increase risk of epithelial ovarian cancer","Protective factors against epithelial ovarian cancer include multiparity, breastfeeding, and combined hormonal contraception"],"references":["Momenimovahed Z, Tiznobaik A, Taheri S, Salehiniya H. Ovarian cancer in the world: epidemiology and risk factors. Int J Womens Health. 2019 Apr 30;11:287-299. doi: 10.2147/IJWH.S197604. PMID: 31118829; PMCID: PMC6500433.","Cho KR, Shih IeM. Ovarian cancer. Annu Rev Pathol. 2009;4:287-313. doi: 10.1146/annurev.pathol.4.110807.092246. PMID: 18842102; PMCID: PMC2679364.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66170"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15730"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66170"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T10:10:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T10:10:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8421"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80848"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0